# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bar-charts-variants
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] A **bar chart** or **bar graph** is a chart or graph that presents categorical data with rectangular bars with heights or lengths proportional to the values that they represent.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] The bars can be plotted vertically or horizontally.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] A vertical bar chart is sometimes called a **column chart** and has been identified as the prototype of charts.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] A bar graph shows comparisons among discrete categories.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] One axis of the chart shows the specific categories being compared, and the other axis represents a measured value.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Some bar graphs present bars clustered or stacked in groups of more than one, showing the values of more than one measured variable.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Many sources consider William Playfair (1759–1824) to have invented the bar chart and the *Exports and Imports of Scotland to and from different parts for one Year from Christmas 1780 to Christmas 1781* graph from his *The Commercial and Political Atlas* to be the first bar chart in history.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Diagrams of the velocity of a constantly accelerating object against time published in *The Latitude of Forms* (attributed to Jacobus de Sancto Martino or, perhaps, to Nicole Oresme) about 300 years before can be interpreted as "proto bar charts".
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Bar graphs/charts provide a visual presentation of categorical data.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Categorical data is a grouping of data into discrete groups, such as months of the year, age group, shoe sizes, and animals.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] These categories are usually qualitative.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] In a column (vertical) bar chart, categories appear along the horizontal axis and the height of the bar corresponds to the value of each category.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Bar charts have a discrete domain of categories, and are usually scaled so that all the data can fit on the chart.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] When there is no natural ordering of the categories being compared, bars on the chart may be arranged in any order.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Bar charts arranged from highest to lowest incidence are called Pareto charts.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] In many cases it is considered correct to use zero as the value at the end of each bar opposite to the end that indicates the data value, because using a non-zero value can make values that are relatively similar have deceptively different bar lengths.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] However, sometimes this approach is not appropriate or not feasible, such as with temperatures in Celsius or Fahrenheit where zero is a somewhat arbitrary value, and with logarithmic charts where "log(0)" would be infinitely far away.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Bar graphs can also be used for more complex comparisons of data with grouped (or "clustered") bar charts, and stacked bar charts.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] In **grouped (clustered) bar charts**, for each categorical group there are two or more bars color-coded to represent a particular grouping.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] For example, a business owner with two stores might make a grouped bar chart with different colored bars to represent each store: the horizontal axis would show the months of the year and the vertical axis would show revenue.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Alternatively, **Stacked bar charts** (also known as **Composite bar charts**) stack bars on top of each other so that the height of the resulting stack shows the combined result.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Unlike a grouped bar chart where each factor is displayed next to another, each with their own bar, the stacked bar chart displays multiple data points stacked in a single row or column.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] This may, for instance, take the form of uniform height bars charting a time series with internal stacked colours indicating the percentage participation of a sub-type of data.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Another example would be a time series displaying total numbers, with internal colors indicating participation in the total by sub-types.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Stacked bar charts are not suited to data sets having both positive and negative values.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Grouped bar charts usually present the information in the same order in each grouping.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Stacked bar charts present the information in the same sequence on each bar.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Variable-width bar charts, sometimes abbreviated *variwide* (bar) charts, are bar charts having bars with non-uniform widths.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Roles of the vertical and horizontal axes may be reversed, depending on the desired application.
[src:bar-charts-variants/bar-chart] Examples of variable-width bar charts are shown at Wikimedia Commons.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Two designers in particular, Vuokko Nurmesniemi, with bold stripes, and Maija Isola, with large simple flowered prints such as the ***Unikko*** poppy, created hundreds of distinctive patterns and helped to make Marimekko a household name across the world.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] The co-founder, Armi Ratia, first considered *Armi* as the company's name, but it was already registered.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Her middle name was Maria, shortened to *Mari*; her husband Viljo thought of different names for women's clothing.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] In her home town of Koivisto, Armi heard people talking about dresses (Finnish: *mekko*), and so she came to the name Marimekko.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Marimekko was founded in 1951 by Viljo and Armi Ratia, after the Viljo's oil-cloth factory project failed and was converted to a garment plant.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Armi asked some artist friends to apply their graphic designs to textiles.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] To show how the fabric could be used, the company then designed and sold a line of simple dresses using their fabric.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] When Finland's leading industrial designer Timo Sarpaneva invited the company to present a fashion show (albeit canceled at short notice) at the 1957 Triennale in Milan, it was an early recognition of fashion as an industrial art and of Marimekko's key role in shaping it to that point.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] The garments were eventually showcased in the nearby Rinascente upscale department store by display manager Giorgio Armani.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Two pioneering designers set the tone for Marimekko: Vuokko Nurmesniemi in the 1950s and Maija Isola in the 1960s.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Nurmesniemi designed the simply striped red and white *Jokapoika* shirt in 1956.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Isola designed the iconic *Unikko* (poppy) print pattern in 1964.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Marimekko's bold fabrics and bright, simple design strongly influenced late 20th-century taste.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Many of the early Marimekko designs, including Isola's *Unikko*, remain in production in the 2010s.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Marimekko spread to America in the 1960s.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] It was introduced to the United States by the architect Benjamin C.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Thompson, who featured them in his Design Research stores.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] They were made famous in the United States by future first lady Jacqueline Kennedy, who bought eight Marimekko dresses which she wore throughout the 1960 United States presidential campaign.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] By 1965, the company employed over 400 staff, and the company was in every aspect of fine design, from fabrics to toys and dinnerware.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] The firm even completely equipped small houses with furnishings.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] In 1985, the company was sold to Amer-yhtymä.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] In the early 1990s, Marimekko was in a bad financial condition and close to bankruptcy.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] It was bought from Amer by Kirsti Paakkanen, who introduced new business methods in the company and helped to revive its popularity.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Later in the 1990s Marimekko achieved publicity in the hit TV series *Sex and the City*.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] The fictional main character of the series, sex-and-relationship columnist Carrie Bradshaw, wore a Marimekko bikini on season 2 and then a Marimekko dress.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] In season 5 the series introduced tablecloths with Marimekko prints.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] In 2005, Marimekko's revenue had quadrupled since Paakkanen's purchase, and its net income had grown 200-fold.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Paakkanen remained CEO of Marimekko and owned 20% of the company via her business Workidea.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] In 2007, Paakkanen announced she would gradually hand over her ownership to Mika Ihamuotila as CEO and biggest owner of the company.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] By 2011 there were 84 stores across the world.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Marimekko products are made in China, India, Thailand, Portugal, Lithuania and other countries.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Fabrics are printed in Marimekko's textile factory in Helsinki, but are not made in Finland.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] The company celebrated its 70th anniversary in 2021 by publishing the book *Marimekko: The Art of Printmaking*.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] The logo of Marimekko has been in use since 1954.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Armi Ratia wanted the logo to be simple and timeless.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Graphic designer Helge Mether-Borgström used modified versions of classic Olivetti typewriter letters to create the logo.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Cindy Babski wrote in the *New York Times* that "There was never any doubt about what the inside label would say.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] The clothes and fabrics, with their striking design and splashes of bold color, were clearly Marimekko.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] In 2007, Heidi Avellan wrote in the Swedish newspaper *Sydsvenskan* that Marimekko was no longer a "statement, just as T-shirts with revolutionary Che Guevara or Palestinian scarves rarely express any political awareness.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Marimekko is paper napkins and rubber boots".
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] She wrote that Marimekko "began with the colourfully striped shirt, *Jokapoika* which Vuokko Nurmesniemi designed in 1956", which became the symbol for new radicalism in academia.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] In 2013, allegations were raised accusing Marimekko of plagiarism.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] In house designer Kristina Isola later admitted copying design elements from 1963 painting by Ukrainian artist Maria Primachenko.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] By the time the accusations were raised, the design had been painted on the body of one of Finnair's planes, and the National Museum of Ukraniain Folk Art, which held the copyright to Primachenko's design, pursued legal action over the incident.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Finnair moved to repaint the plane as quickly as possible.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] After the incident was raised, other works by Marimekko were identified to be alleged to have strong similarities to works previously released by artists Maria Jauhiainen, Markus Lepo and Heljä Liukko-Sundström.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] Five designs came under suspicion, with Marimekko defending against some claims, and trying to settle others.
[src:bar-charts-variants/marimekko] In the case of Lepo's design, Marimekko's CEO later apologised for misleading consumers about the originality of the designs.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] A **Pareto chart** is a type of chart that contains both bars and a line graph, where individual values are represented in descending order by bars, and the cumulative total is represented by the line.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] The chart is named for the Pareto principle, which, in turn, derives its name from Vilfredo Pareto, a noted Italian economist.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] Its purpose is to assess the most frequently occurring defects by category.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] The left vertical axis is the frequency of occurrence, but it can alternatively represent cost or another important unit of measure.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] The right vertical axis is the cumulative percentage of the total number of occurrences, total cost, or total of the particular unit of measure.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] Because the values are in decreasing order, the cumulative function is a concave function.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] To take the example below, in order to lower the amount of late arrivals by 78%, it is sufficient to solve the first three issues.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] The Pareto Chart demonstrates a power law relationship between the rank of a quality issue and that issue's contribution to cost.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] This means one can find a linear relationship on a log-log plot.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] The purpose of the Pareto chart is to highlight the most important among a (typically large) set of factors.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] In quality control, Pareto charts are useful to find the defects to prioritize in order to observe the greatest overall improvement.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] It often represents the most common sources of defects, the highest occurring type of defect, or the most frequent reasons for customer complaints, and so on.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] Wilkinson (2006) devised an algorithm for producing statistically based acceptance limits (similar to confidence intervals) for each bar in the Pareto chart.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] These charts can be generated by simple spreadsheet programs, specialized statistical software tools, and online quality charts generators.
[src:bar-charts-variants/pareto-chart] The Pareto chart is one of the seven basic tools of quality control.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] A **population pyramid** (age structure diagram) or "**age-sex pyramid**" is a graphical illustration of the distribution of a population (typically that of a country or region of the world) by age groups and sex; it typically takes the shape of a pyramid when the population is growing.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Males are usually shown on the left and females on the right, and they may be measured in absolute numbers or as a percentage of the total population.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] The pyramid can be used to visualize the age of a particular population.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] It is also used in ecology to determine the overall age distribution of a population; an indication of the reproductive capabilities and likelihood of the continuation of a species.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Number of people per unit area of land is called population density.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] A population pyramid often contains continuous stacked-histogram bars, making it a horizontal bar diagram.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] The population size is shown on the x-axis (horizontal) while the age-groups are represented on the y-axis (vertical).
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] The size of each bar can be displayed either as a percentage of the total population or as a raw number.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Males are conventionally shown on the left and females on the right.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Population pyramids are often viewed as the most effective way to graphically depict the age and distribution of a population, partly because of the very clear image these pyramids provide.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] A great deal of information about the population broken down by age and sex can be read from a population pyramid, and this can shed light on the extent of development and other aspects of the population.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] The measures of central tendency (mean, median, and mode) should be considered when assessing a population pyramid.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] For example, the average age could be used to determine the type of population in a particular region.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] A population with an average age of 15 would be very young compared to one with an average age of 55.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Population statistics are often mid-year numbers.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] A series of population pyramids could give a clear picture of how a country transitions from high to low fertility rates.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] If the pyramid has a broad base, this indicates that a relatively high proportion of the population lies in the youngest age band, such as ages 0–14, which suggests that the fertility rate of the country is high and above replacement fertility level.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] If a population is below replacement fertility level, the older population is declining with age, due to a combination of mortality and an increase in the number of births over time.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] There are usually more females than males in the older age ranges since, for a variety of reasons, women have a greater life expectancy.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] The shape of the pyramid can also reveal the age-dependency ratio of a population.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Populations with a high proportion of children and/or of elderly people have a higher dependency ratio.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] This ratio refers to how many old and young people are dependent on the working-age groups (often defined as ages 15–64).
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] According to Weeks' *Population: an Introduction to Concepts and Issues,* population pyramids can be used to predict the future, known as a population forecast.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Population momentum, when a population's birth rates continue to increase even after fertility rate has declined to replacement level, can even be predicted if a population has a low mortality rate since the population will continue to grow.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] This then brings up the term doubling time, which is used to predict when the population will double in size.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Lastly, a population pyramid can even give insight into the economic status of a country from the age stratification since the distribution of supplies is not evenly distributed through a population.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] In the demographic transition model, the size and shape of population pyramids vary.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] In stage one of the demographic transition model, the pyramids have the most defined shape.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] They have the ideal big base and a skinny top.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] In stage two, the pyramid looks similar but starts to widen in the middle age groups.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] In stage three, the pyramids start to round out and look similar in shape to a tombstone.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] In stage four, there is a decrease in the younger age groups.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] This causes the base of the widened pyramid to narrow.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Lastly, in stage five, the pyramid starts to take on the shape of a kite as the base continues to decrease.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] The shape of the population is dependent upon what the economy is like in the country.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] More developed countries can be found in stages three, four, and five, while the least developed countries have a population represented by the pyramids in stages one and two.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Each country will have a different population pyramid.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] However, population pyramids can be categorised into three types: stationary, expansive, or constrictive.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] These types have been identified by the fertility and mortality rates of a country.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] A pyramid can be described as stationary if the percentages of population (age and sex) remain approximately constant over time.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] In a stationary population, the numbers of births and death roughly balance one another.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] A population pyramid that is very wide at the younger ages, characteristic of countries with a high birth rate and perhaps low life expectancy therefore leading to high death rate.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] The population is said to be fast-growing, and the size of each birth cohort increases each year.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] A population pyramid that is narrowed at the bottom.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] The population is generally older on average, as the country has long life expectancy, a low death rate, but also a low birth rate.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] This may suggest that in future there may be a high dependency ratio due to reducing numbers at working ages.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] This is a typical pattern for a very developed country, with a high level of education, easy access to and incentive to use birth control, good health care, and few negative environmental factors.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Gary Fuller (1995) described a youth bulge as a type of expansive pyramid.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Heinsohn claims that most historical periods of social unrest lacking external triggers (such as rapid climatic changes or other catastrophic changes of the environment) and most genocides can be readily explained as a result of a built-up youth bulge.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] This factor has been also used to account for the Arab Spring events and the rise of extremist populism in the 2010s.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Economic recessions, such as the Great Depression of the 1930s and the late 2000s Great Recession, are also claimed to be explained in part due to a large youth population who cannot find jobs.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Youth bulge can be seen as one factor among many in explaining social unrest and uprisings in society.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] A 2016 study finds that youth bulges increase the chances of non-ethnic civil wars, but not ethnic civil wars.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] A large population of adolescents entering the labor force and electorate strains at the seams of the economy and polity, which were designed for smaller populations.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] This creates unemployment and alienation unless new opportunities are created quickly enough – in which case a 'demographic dividend' accrues because productive workers outweigh young and elderly dependents.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] Yet the 16–29 age range is associated with risk-taking, especially among males.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] In general, youth bulges in developing countries are associated with higher unemployment and, as a result, a heightened risk of violence and political instability.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] For Cincotta and Doces (2011), the transition to more mature age structures is almost a sine qua non for democratization.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] To reverse the effects of youth bulges, specific policies such as creating more jobs, improving family planning programs, and reducing overall infant mortality rates should be a priority.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] The Middle East and North Africa are currently experiencing a prominent youth bulge.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] "Across the Middle East, countries have experienced a pronounced increase in the size of their youth populations over recent decades, both in total numbers and as a percentage of the total population.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] It is estimated that around 65% of the regional population is under the age of 25.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] The youth bulge in the Middle East and North Africa has been favorably compared to that of East Asia, which harnessed this human capital and saw huge economic growth in recent decades.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] The youth bulge has been referred to by the Middle East Youth Initiative as a demographic gift, which, if engaged, could fuel regional economic growth and development.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] "While the growth of the youth population imposes supply pressures on education systems and labor markets, it also means that a growing share of the overall population is made up of those considered to be of working age; and thus not dependent on the economic activity of others.
[src:bar-charts-variants/population-pyramid] In turn, this declining dependency ratio can have a positive impact on overall economic growth, creating a demographic dividend.
